13 Apr 2015: Nicaragua quarantines US embassy staffer over Ebola fears
https://uk.news.yahoo.com/nicaragua-quarantines-us-embassy-staffer-over-ebola-fears-195705828.html
[A 51-year-old USA Embassy staffer, who has not been identified, traveled to Liberia for work where he "spent time in health facilities where Ebola patients are being treated." Upon his return on Sun 12 Apr 2015, he has been restricted by the Nicaraguan government from leaving his Managua home, while Nicaragua tries to coordinate his safe removal from the country and return to the USA. The USA denied the staffer was exposed to Ebola virus. The United States Centers for Disease Control had examined him, and confirmed he had no Ebola virus symptoms. Nicaragua's health ministry had cleared him for return to Nicaragua]

13 Apr 2015 Poland: Suspected Ebola patient taken into Warsaw hospital
http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/203313,Suspected-Ebola-patient-taken-into-Warsaw-hospital
[Male patient (a pilot) hospitalized at Warsaw Hospital for Infectious Diseases after returning from abroad. Blood testing for Ebola and malaria was done; 1st Ebola test returned Sunday night (12 Apr 2015) as negative. 2nd Ebola test will be performed Mon 13 Apr 2015]

13 Apr 2015 Sierra Leone: Pros and cons of Sierra Leone's Ebola lockdowns http://allafrica.com/stories/201504132030.html?viewall=1

14 Apr 2015 Sierra Leone: Children return to school in Sierra Leone post Ebola outbreak
http://www.breakingnews.ie/world/children-return-to-school-in-sierra-leone-post-ebola-outbreak-671787.html
[Children have not been attending school since July 2014, and will be asked to attend schools on Saturdays to make up for the time the school days missed because of the Ebola virus outbreak]

15 Apr 2015 Sierra Leone: Classes resume in Sierra Leone after Ebola crisis -- but pregnant teens are banned
https://news.vice.com/article/classes-resume-in-sierra-leone-after-ebola-crisis-but-pregnant-teens-are-banned

[Comment provided by John James, Communications Specialist, Head of External Relations & Advocacy, United Nations Children's Fund: "We give a range of support to all mothers in Sierra Leone including helping the Free Healthcare Initiative which covers pregnant and lactating women, and children under 5. We are currently advocating the Ministry of Education, with our UN partners, to ensure that all children, including pregnant girls, have access to education, including for taking part in examinations." - Mod.JW]

